<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,334,368,394]" box="[189,334,368,394]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,368,394]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,368,394]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,860,414,476]" box="[234,465,414,441]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,348,415,441]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<typeStatus box="[234,348,415,441]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Holotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[364,457,414,441]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[196,1394,1107,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[195,1395,1106,1887]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 3. Orphnus valeriae sp. nov. A. Habitus. B–C. Head in dorsal and apical view. D. Aedeagus in lateral view. E. Parameres in dorsal view. F. Labels of holotype. G. Abdomen in dorsal view. H. Stridulatory field. A–F. Holotype. G–H. Paratypes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850311/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,860,414,476]" box="[189,860,450,476]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Body length 
<quantity box="[341,447,450,476]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.16" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="11.6">11.6 mm</quantity>
. Colour uniformly blackish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,515,682]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Anterior margin of frontoclypeus slightly convex in the middle, slightly sinuate aside the medial convexity, rounded laterally, with a narrow border (
<figureCitation box="[782,873,550,576]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[196,1394,1107,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[195,1395,1106,1887]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 3. Orphnus valeriae sp. nov. A. Habitus. B–C. Head in dorsal and apical view. D. Aedeagus in lateral view. E. Parameres in dorsal view. F. Labels of holotype. G. Abdomen in dorsal view. H. Stridulatory field. A–F. Holotype. G–H. Paratypes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850311/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Frontoclypeus with a trapezoidal transverse process medially approximately on the line connecting anterior margins canthi (
<figureCitation box="[1118,1210,585,612]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[196,1394,1107,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[195,1395,1106,1887]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 3. Orphnus valeriae sp. nov. A. Habitus. B–C. Head in dorsal and apical view. D. Aedeagus in lateral view. E. Parameres in dorsal view. F. Labels of holotype. G. Abdomen in dorsal view. H. Stridulatory field. A–F. Holotype. G–H. Paratypes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850311/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Frontoclypeus finely punctate anteriad of the process and coarsely punctate with elongated punctures posteriad of the process.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1398,721,783]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Eyes relatively large: width about 1/5 the distance between eyes in dorsal view. Antennae 10-segmented, without malformed segments.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1398,822,989]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Pronotum widely rounded laterally, almost as wide as elytra, 1.4 times wider than length, 0.75 length of elytra (
<figureCitation box="[271,359,857,883]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1860,1886]" captionTargetBox="[228,1350,266,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[227,1357,265,1825]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 1. — A–M. Orphnus giganteus Paulian, 1948. A–B. Habitus. C–D. Head in dorsal and apical view. E–G. Antennae. H. Aedeagus in lateral view. I. Parameres in dorsal view. J. Abdomen in dorsal view. K–L. Stridulatory field. M. Habitus. — N. O. renaudi sp. nov., holotype, habitus. — O. O. ferrierei sp. nov., holotype, habitus. — P. O. valeriae sp. nov., holotype, habitus. — Q. O. parastrangulatus sp. nov., holotype, habitus. — R. O. strangulatus Paulian, 1948, habitus. M–R = not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850303/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 1P</figureCitation>
). Anterior border wide, with smooth posterior margin. Basal border narrow, keel-shaped, separated from pronotal disc by a smooth groove. Pronotal disc anteromedially distinctly flattened and slightly concave. Surface of pronotum covered with dense, coarse, rounded to elongated punctures except for a V-shaped almost smooth and slightly convex area in the centre.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1150,1028,1054]" lastBlockId="10.[189,1399,265,399]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="11" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Scutellum subtriangular, narrowly rounded apically, about 1/13 the length of elytra. Elytra 1.07 times wider than long, without humeral humps. Elytra widest in basal ¼, with widely rounded lateral margins. First five striae faintly visible as very shallow grooves, without rows of punctures. Elytra covered with rather sparse punctures becoming denser towards the base; sculpture of the base is rasp-shaped.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850311" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3850311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850311/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" startId="9.[189,232,1929,1955]" targetBox="[196,1394,1107,1876]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1398,1929,2026]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,264,1929,1955]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Frolov &amp; Akhmetova, 2016" authorityName="Frolov &amp; Akhmetova" authorityYear="2016" box="[270,474,1929,1955]" class="Insecta" family="Orphnidae" genus="Orphnus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valeriae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[270,474,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Orphnus valeriae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[480,568,1930,1956]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[573,594,1929,1955]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">A</emphasis>
. Habitus. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[711,766,1929,1955]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">B–C</emphasis>
. Head in dorsal and apical view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1143,1164,1930,1956]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">D</emphasis>
. Aedeagus in lateral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[260,280,1965,1991]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">E</emphasis>
. Parameres in dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[607,625,1965,1991]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">F</emphasis>
. Labels of holotype. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[878,901,1964,1990]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">G</emphasis>
. Abdomen in dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1220,1243,1965,1991]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">H</emphasis>
. Stridulatory field. A–F. Holotype. G–H. Paratypes.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,999,437,465]" box="[189,999,437,465]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Brachypterous. Wings vestigial, narrow, about ¾ the length of elytra.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1181,502,530]" box="[189,1181,502,530]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Stridulatory field: carinae separated by 1/30 length of the field in central ¼ 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1046,1060,502,516]" fontSize="6" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">rd</superScript>
(
<figureCitation box="[1073,1167,504,530]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[196,1394,1107,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[195,1395,1106,1887]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 3. Orphnus valeriae sp. nov. A. Habitus. B–C. Head in dorsal and apical view. D. Aedeagus in lateral view. E. Parameres in dorsal view. F. Labels of holotype. G. Abdomen in dorsal view. H. Stridulatory field. A–F. Holotype. G–H. Paratypes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850311/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 3H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1398,569,666]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Abdominal sternite 8 medially longer than sternites 6 and 7 combined; sternites 6 and 7 approximately of the same length. Pygidium feebly visible from above. Plectrum trapezoidal, elongated (
<figureCitation box="[1287,1385,604,631]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[196,1394,1107,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[195,1395,1106,1887]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 3. Orphnus valeriae sp. nov. A. Habitus. B–C. Head in dorsal and apical view. D. Aedeagus in lateral view. E. Parameres in dorsal view. F. Labels of holotype. G. Abdomen in dorsal view. H. Stridulatory field. A–F. Holotype. G–H. Paratypes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850311/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
). Lateral plate of the second abdominal sternite relatively small, shorter than plectrum, with acute apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1399,705,802]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Aedeagus with relatively long parameres (0.58 length of phallobase). Apices of the parameres widely rounded in dorsal view and acute, slightly curved downwards in lateral view, without excavations (
<figureCitation box="[198,266,775,802]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[189,232,1929,1955]" captionTargetBox="[196,1394,1107,1876]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[195,1395,1106,1887]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 3. Orphnus valeriae sp. nov. A. Habitus. B–C. Head in dorsal and apical view. D. Aedeagus in lateral view. E. Parameres in dorsal view. F. Labels of holotype. G. Abdomen in dorsal view. H. Stridulatory field. A–F. Holotype. G–H. Paratypes." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850311" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850311/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
D–E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,325,841,902]" box="[234,325,841,867]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,325,841,867]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,325,841,902]" box="[189,313,876,902]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,307,941,967]" box="[189,307,941,967]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,307,941,967]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,307,941,967]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Variation</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1399,988,1085]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Body length of 
<typeStatus box="[372,484,989,1015]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">paratypes</typeStatus>
varies from 11.0– 
<quantity box="[700,806,988,1015]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="12.5">12.5 mm</quantity>
. In one specimen, antennomeres 5 and 6 are partly fused. The variation in body size, shape and size of the frontoclypeal process and in the sculpture of the pronotum is notably small among the reasonably large type series.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,342,1124,1150]" box="[189,342,1124,1150]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,342,1124,1150]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,342,1124,1150]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,1399,1170,1233]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
The species is known from three localities, two in the foothills of the Eastern Arc Mountains and one in coastal forest some 
<quantity box="[421,495,1206,1232]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="km" value="40.0">40 km</quantity>
inland (
<figureCitation box="[592,664,1206,1233]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1966,1992]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,1011,1923]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[189,1398,1009,1925]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 6. Orphnus (Phornus) spp. Locality map. Orphnus parastrangulatus sp. nov. is not mapped, because there are no more or less precise locality data available for this species." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3850323" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3850323/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
